post_text:
Hello, Parents of Native Students:

The Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) of 2016, the reauthorization of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965 (ESEA) provides increased opportunities for tribal leaders and school districts to work together on behalf of American Indian and Alaska Native students.

We are excited to forward the Indian Policies and Procedures (IPPs) and to give you an opportunity to provide input and comments into these procedures. The Indian Policies and Procedures can be found at the following URL or you may request a copy from your local school.
http://www.lksd.org/common/pages/DisplayFile.aspx?itemId=10611402

Please take the time to review the IPPs and forward your comments to Minnie Chase at minnie_chase@lksd.org. You may also mail or request the Principal forward your input to LKSD, attention Minnie Chase.

Thank You,

Minnie Chase

post_text:
Dear LKSD Families:

The Alaska Department of Health and Social Services (DHSS) and the Alaska Department of Education and Early Development (DEED) have collaborated to provide the Alaska Smart Start 2020 framework, shown below. The Department of Health and Social Services is responsible for defining and establishing the parameters for how schools will safely operate, once opened, in low, medium, and high risk environments. Once those parameters are set by DHSS, LKSD administration will finalize district plans that outline how LKSD will deliver education under each of the three environments, focusing specifically on conditions for learning, continuity of learning, and capacities for learning. LKSD will provide updates for all stakeholders via the district's website and Facebook page as plans for LKSD's restart/reentry are finalized. We look forward to having staff and students back on campus in August.

post_text:
Hayden Lieb, a senior at Bethel Regional High School, has been announced as one of the three finalists for the Alaska Sports Hall of Fame 2020 Pride of Alaska Youth Award!

"The Pride of Alaska Youth Award honors consistent excellence in athletic competition. It rewards an athlete or team that not only excelled in sports but did so with integrity and sportsmanship."

"Hayden Lieb became the 14th Alaska high school wrestler to win four state titles as an individual. He added three more team championships for Bethel. The high school All-American finished his career with a 139-12 record and signed with NCAA D1 University of Wyoming. In his final match at the 2019 state championships, Lieb defeated a Petersburg wrestler 15-0 at 160 pounds to help Bethel take a narrow victory over Glennallen."

The winner will be announced on May 6 at 2 p.m via Facebook Live on the Alaska Sports Hall of Fame Facebook page.

post_text: Let's see how many of our students and parents we can get to be a part of this! Check out the details for more information!
shared_text:
KYUK
April 8 at 12:01 PM ·

Join KYUK and Pamyua for a Yuraq Music Video Collaboration!

Quarantine has us stuck inside but that can't keep us from dancing. Send us a Yuraq Selfie video to "Tarvarnauramken"/"Blessing Song" and we'll produce one video with all of us dancing together.

Here's what you need to know:
- Send your video to wellness@kyuk.org by Tuesday, April 14

-Please film yourself dancing to "Tarvarnauramken" or "Blessing Song" as performed and recorded by Pamyua in this YouTube link:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fdwNJX72lJM&fbclid=IwAR23VdvbDgnMvlmFzQuo9bZAcyXDP-ofyl3ouBEFWneKbyvuOwgSLl3CT_8
Use this version of the song so that we are all dancing to the same beat.

-Please film the video horizontally or in landscape.

- Give us some attitude. Make us laugh or make us cry. Wear your best qaspeq, your favorite Y-K Delta hoodie or a homemade mask. Express yourself through your performance and clothing and don't be afraid to show us what you got!

-Stay Safe and Healthy!

-HAVE FUN!!!

post_text:
Hello Bethel,

Bethel Schools will have breakfast and lunch ready for pick-up at 11 AM at your child’s school. Meals for multiple students may be picked up by a delegate from each household as long as the students all are enrolled at the same site. Families that have students at multiple schools will need to pick up meals from each school where the students are enrolled. During these meal pickups please practice social distancing, stay at least 6ft from each other. Additionally, gather in small groups and maintain distance from each other.

BRHS:
11:00-12:00 ---- 7th and 8th grade
12:00-12:45 ---- 9th through 12th grade

Gladys Jung:
11:00-12:00 ---- 3rd and 4th grade
12:00-1:00 ---- 5th and 6th grade

ME:
11:00-12:00 ---- PreK and Kindergarten
12:00-1:00 ---- 1st and 2nd grade

Ayaprun:
11:00-1:00 ---- Kindergarten through 6th grade

post_text:
Please read the attached document from the LKSD Food Service Department regarding student to-go meals during the week of March 16-20, 2020.

------------------------------------------------------
From document:

In light of the COVID-19 situation in Alaska, LKSD has made the decision to cancel classes for al sites during the week of March 16-20, 2020. In an effort to continue to provide nutritious meals to students during school closures, the State of Alaska has granted school districts waivers to allow to-go meals to be distributed by sites. The LKSD Food Service department, in conjunction with NMS, is working on a plan to ensure that all students have access to breakfast and lunch during school closures due to the COVID-19.

Details on meal pick up for each site will be available as they are finalized over the weekend, and to-go meal service will begin on Monday, March 16th.

Please call or email your child's schools with any questions.

Thank you,
Marybeth Whalen, SNS
Food Service Director
Lower Kuskokwim School District

post_text:
The Lower Kuskokwim School District (LKSD) is announcing a cancelation of classes for all students (including village schools) for one week, March 16th– 20th 2020. During this closure, school staff are expected to report to work and will be formulating plans for the continuation of education services should longer school closures become necessary. All non-essential travel in and out-of-state and the district is cancelled as are all student activities, pending further notice. This includes travel previously approved by the LKSD Board.

This cancelation of classes is in response to the rapidly-evolving COVID-19 situation and comes after careful consideration and communication with the Alaska Department of Education, the Commissioner of Education, and State health officials. It also comes with deliberate consideration of our mission, the safety of our students and staff, as well as for the protection of our communities.

LKSD staff will be notified directly with further guidance by the end of the day on Friday, March 13th.

LKSD’s student board representatives wrapped up the Youth Advocacy Institute (YAI) this afternoon. They had a chance to sit in with numerous representatives and senators to advocate for issues that pertained to their communities and for students across their school district.

The students spent their last day at the Mendenhall Glacier.

“It was an amazing experience and I got to learn a lot about how our state is run. Juneau is a beautiful place with a vibrant energy and culture.” - Ethan Sundown

“I never thought I would step foot in the state capital building. Also, being introduced to both of our legislators was awesome!”
- Jaden Andrew

“I enjoyed seeing and meeting our representatives. I never thought I was going to meet them. I was happy to come to Juneau to learn from my peers and our school board.”
- Eliza Enoch

The 2020 census officially starts in an Alaskan fishing village along the Bering Sea. Starting the count there in January, when the ground is frozen, makes it easier to reach far-flung communities.

post_text: Have at look at this amazing art installation by Clayton Conner at Z.J. Williams School in Napaskiak!
shared_text:
Alaska Art Colony
September 22, 2019 at 4:49 PM ·

The newest creation at Z.J. Williams School in Napaskiak, Alaska!! This very unique piece created by artist Clayton Conner blends fine art with objects such as driftwood, fishing nets, and even fish painted on wood that are mounted and are literally "leaping" off the surface! This piece of installation art is the newest addition to this school, and will be followed by several other breathtaking pieces that are pending. This beautiful art is best appreciated in person, to get the full impact of the 3D effect.

The newest creation at Z.J. Williams School in Napaskiak, Alaska!! This very unique piece created by artist Clayton Conner blends fine art with objects such as driftwood, fishing nets, and even fish painted on wood that are mounted and are literally "leaping" off the surface! This piece of installation art is the newest addition to this school, and will be followed by several other breathtaking pieces that are pending. This beautiful art is best appreciated in person, to get the full impact of the 3D effect.

Hello, Parents of Native Students:

The Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) of 2016, the reauthorization of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965 (ESEA), provides increased opportunities for tribal leaders and school districts to work together on behalf of American Indian and Alaska Native students.

We are excited to forward a link to the Indian Policies and Procedures (IPPs) and to give you an opportunity to provide input and comments into these procedures. The Indian Policies and Procedures may be accessed at the following URL or you may request a copy from the local school:

http://www.lksd.org/common/pages/DisplayFile.aspx?itemId=10611402

Please take the time to review the IPPs and forward your comments to Minnie Chase at minnie_chase@lksd.org. You may also mail or request that your Site Administrator forward your input to LKSD, attention Minnie Chase.

Thank you.

Here we are at Day 2 of the LKSD Annual Fall Conference-Quyurramta 2019- Leading with the Heart! #LKSDAFC
- Assistant Superintendent Kimberly Hankins opened the morning with a discussion of Relationships and Rigor in the classroom and spoke on the "Warm Demander" educator. "Judith Kleinfeld coined the term Warm Demanders when describing teachers who most successfully supported student achievement. The "Warm Demander" teacher expects great things from their students, convince them of their own brilliance, and help them reach their potential in a disciplined, structured environment.
- Dr. Panigkaq Agatha John-Shields then provided the morning's Keynote. Dr. Panigkaq Agatha John-Shields works as the Term Assistant Professor in Indigenous Education/Educational Leadership at UAA. She opened her Keynote by inviting LKSD to Yuraq together.
- It was also with great pleasure that we announced Mr. Jon LaValle of Bethel Regional High School as LKSD's Teacher of the Year for 2019! Congratulations, Mr. LaValle!

post_text:
This morning we kicked off our Annual Fall Conference-Quyurramta 2019 – Leading with the Heart. The conference was opened by Superintendent Dan Walker and followed with a Welcome and Keynote by Dr. Steven Atwater.
Dr. Atwater was named Alaska's 2013 superintendent of the year and currently works as the Executive Dean of the Alaska College of Education of the University of Alaska Southeast. Dr. Atwater spoke about the importance of building meaningful relationships with our students and connecting culture to the content taught in our classrooms.
We are so excited to have our LKSD team of education professionals together for the next three days of professional development!

Alaska Governor's Council on Disabilities & Special Education
July 24, 2019 at 8:35 AM ·

New Council Member Highlight: Joshua Gill

“My name is Joshua Gill. First and foremost, I am the husband to my beautiful wife and father of five children, ages 24, 13, 7, 6, and 5. My 7-year-old daughter has Down Syndrome and has been a tremendous joy in our life. I currently live in Bethel and have lived throughout the Kuskokwim region for the past 16 years. As part of my employment with the Lower Kuskokwim School District, I have traveled extensively throughout the Kuskokwim Region and have seen as well as personally experienced the challenges of having a loved one with special needs. I hope to use my appointment to this board to advocate for all Alaskans with special needs, especially those that live in Rural Alaska. All Alaskans with special needs deserve a voice, but particularly those who live in under-served, remote areas of the state where there can be limited access to healthcare and services.”

Do you know a youth hero who deserves a $1,500 scholarship and recognition for their efforts?
@Alaska Communications and @Boys & Girls Clubs – Alaska are now accepting nominations for the
2019 #SummerOfHeroes program. Learn more: http://bit.ly/1ILo8uE

Who can be nominated for the youth recognition program?
- Any resident of Alaska between the ages of 6 and 18 can be considered for the program.
- Any youth who meet the criteria can self-nominate or be nominated by someone they know
such as a parent, guardian, sibling, teacher, coach, mentor or friend.

A hero can be any youth who has:
- volunteered or raised significant funds for a cause,
- made a difference in school through education or sports,
- inspired others to take action,
- considered others’ needs before their own,
- made a significant contribution to his or her community, or
- other activity to better the community.

When does the Summer of Heroes program start and end?
The nomination period for “hero” candidates runs from April 2 through June 28.
